{id:'q3_ev_001',subject:'Environment',node:'ev1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Ecology',
q:'Ecological Footprint measures:',
opts:['Carbon emissions of a country only','Area of biologically productive land/water needed to produce resources consumed and absorb waste generated','Biodiversity richness of an ecosystem','Annual water consumption of a nation'],
ans:1,
explain:'Ecological Footprint = total productive area needed to support a population\'s consumption and waste absorption. Earth Overshoot Day marks when humanity exhausts annual biological budget.',
wrongExplain:'India\'s per-capita footprint is relatively low vs developed nations. But total footprint is large due to 1.4 billion population. Biocapacity deficit = ecological debtor nation.'},

{id:'q3_ev_002',subject:'Environment',node:'ev2',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'Paris Agreement',
q:'The "Ratchet Mechanism" in the Paris Agreement requires:',
opts:['A carbon market trading tool','Each country\'s new NDC every 5 years must be more ambitious than the previous one — no backsliding allowed','Financial penalty for missing emission targets','A UN carbon credit system'],
ans:1,
explain:'Ratchet Mechanism (Art 3): Countries submit NDCs every 5 years. Each must show "progression" — cannot reduce ambition. Global Stocktake (first at COP28 Dubai 2023) assesses collective progress.',
wrongExplain:'Current NDCs put world on 2.5-2.7°C trajectory — far from 1.5°C. Ratchet mechanism is designed to close this gap over successive rounds. COP29 NCQG ($300B finance) is separate from NDC ambition.'},

{id:'q3_ev_003',subject:'Environment',node:'ev3',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'Extinction',
q:'The current biodiversity crisis is distinguished from past mass extinctions because:',
opts:['It is caused by a meteor impact like the last one','It is human-caused — first anthropogenic mass extinction (habitat loss, overexploitation, climate change, invasive species)','Species are dying at the same rate as before','It only affects tropical regions'],
ans:1,
explain:'6th mass extinction (Anthropocene): Human-caused. Species dying 1,000-10,000x background rate. IPBES (biodiversity equivalent of IPCC) documents the scale. 1 million species threatened.',
wrongExplain:'5 previous mass extinctions were all natural: Ordovician, Devonian, Permian (worst — 96% species lost), Triassic, Cretaceous (dinosaurs). All had natural triggers. Current = human activities.'},

{id:'q3_ev_004',subject:'Environment',node:'ev3',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Project Tiger',
q:'Project Tiger was launched in India in:',
opts:['1952','1973 — Jim Corbett National Park was the first reserve','1980','1992'],
ans:1,
explain:'Project Tiger 1973: Tiger population was 1,827 (1972 census). Now ~3,167 (2022 census) — India has ~70% of world\'s wild tigers. NTCA (National Tiger Conservation Authority) oversees 54 tiger reserves.',
wrongExplain:'Success story of wildlife conservation. Project Elephant (1992), Project Snow Leopard (2009), Project Crocodile (1975) — know the major wildlife conservation projects.'},

{id:'q3_ev_005',subject:'Environment',node:'ev4',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'EPR',
q:'Extended Producer Responsibility (EPR) means:',
opts:['Government bears all waste management costs','Producers are responsible for collecting and recycling their products at end-of-life — waste management cost shifted to producers','Only consumers pay for waste disposal','Municipalities handle all industrial waste'],
ans:1,
explain:'EPR: Manufacturer takes back and recycles products after consumer use. India\'s EPR framework covers plastic packaging, e-waste, battery waste, tyre waste under Environment Protection Act.',
wrongExplain:'EPR rules: producers register with CPCB, set collection targets, report compliance annually. Can outsource to PROs (Producer Responsibility Organisations). Shifts cost from taxpayer to producer.'},

{id:'q3_ev_006',subject:'Environment',node:'ev2',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'Climate Targets',
q:'The Paris Agreement\'s temperature target is to limit warming above:',
opts:['Current average temperature','Pre-industrial levels (approximately 1850) — well below 2°C, pursue 1.5°C','1990 baseline levels','Year 2000 temperature levels'],
ans:1,
explain:'Paris Agreement: Well below 2°C and pursue 1.5°C above pre-industrial (circa 1850) levels. Current warming = ~1.2°C above pre-industrial. IPCC: every 0.5°C matters enormously.',
wrongExplain:'Pre-industrial chosen as baseline because that\'s before human fossil fuel use significantly began. Carbon budget for 1.5°C is rapidly depleting — may be crossed in early 2030s.'},

{id:'q3_ev_007',subject:'Environment',node:'ev5',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Energy Storage',
q:'Pumped Hydro Storage (PHS) is important for renewable energy because:',
opts:['It generates electricity from ocean waves','It stores excess solar/wind power by pumping water uphill; releases it through turbines when power demand is high','It converts geothermal energy to electricity','It purifies groundwater while generating power'],
ans:1,
explain:'PHS: Excess solar/wind → pump water uphill (store energy). When needed → water flows down through turbines (release energy). Accounts for 95% of world\'s grid-scale energy storage. India has 4.7 GW PHS capacity.',
wrongExplain:'Challenge with renewables: intermittency (no sun at night, wind variable). Storage solutions: Li-ion batteries, PHS, green hydrogen. PHS is cheapest for large-scale long-duration storage.'},

{id:'q3_ev_008',subject:'Environment',node:'ev3',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Forest Cover',
q:'India\'s forest and tree cover as per Forest Survey of India (FSI) 2021 stands at approximately:',
opts:['15% of geographical area','24.62% of geographical area (33% is National Forest Policy target)','40% of geographical area','10% of geographical area'],
ans:1,
explain:'FSI 2021: Total forest + tree cover = 24.62% of India\'s 329 million hectares. Short of the 33% target. Madhya Pradesh = highest absolute cover. Mizoram = highest % (84%).',
wrongExplain:'India added ~1,540 sq km of forest cover between 2019-21. NE India and Western Ghats are biodiversity hotspots within this. Degraded forests are a bigger concern than deforestation.'},

{id:'q3_ev_009',subject:'Environment',node:'ev4',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'Air Pollution',
q:'Stubble burning in Punjab-Haryana contributes to Delhi\'s winter air pollution primarily through:',
opts:['Local circulation of Delhi\'s own pollution','North-westerly winds carrying PM2.5, PM10, CO from burning fields to Delhi in October-November','Only industrial emissions from satellite towns','Vehicle emissions alone'],
ans:1,
explain:'Post-kharif harvest (Oct-Nov): Stubble burning generates massive PM2.5. North-westerly winds carry it 300-400 km to Delhi. Contributes 25-40% of Delhi\'s PM2.5 during peak winter season.',
wrongExplain:'Happy Seeder machine allows in-situ management (planting next crop without burning). Adoption slow due to cost. Economic rationality: burning cheapest for farmers, but health externality borne by Delhi.'},

{id:'q3_ev_010',subject:'Environment',node:'ev2',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'Ramsar',
q:'The Ramsar Convention specifically protects:',
opts:['Endangered species globally','Wetlands of international importance — their wise use and conservation','Migratory birds only','Marine ecosystems exclusively'],
ans:1,
explain:'Ramsar Convention (1971, Ramsar, Iran): Conservation and wise use of wetlands. India has 80 Ramsar sites (2024) — highest in Asia. Criteria include size, biodiversity, hydrological importance.',
wrongExplain:'CITES = trade in endangered species. CMS = migratory species. CBD = biodiversity broadly. Ramsar = wetlands specifically. India\'s Ramsar sites: Chilika Lake, Sundarbans, Loktak, Wular Lake, Keoladeo.'},

{id:'q3_ev_011',subject:'Environment',node:'ev5',difficulty:'medium',year:2022,topic:'Renewable Energy',
q:'India\'s target for non-fossil energy capacity by 2030 (per PANCHAMRIT commitments) is:',
opts:['100 GW solar only','500 GW non-fossil energy capacity total','200 GW combined renewables','Only hydropower expansion'],
ans:1,
explain:'PANCHAMRIT (COP26 Glasgow 2021): India\'s 5 commitments include 500 GW non-fossil capacity + 50% electricity from renewables by 2030. India = 3rd largest installed solar capacity (~82 GW by 2024).',
wrongExplain:'100 GW was an older solar-specific target. PANCHAMRIT also includes: 1 billion tonne emission reduction, -45% emission intensity, Net Zero by 2070.'},

{id:'q3_ev_012',subject:'Environment',node:'ev6',difficulty:'hard',year:2021,topic:'NGT',
q:'National Green Tribunal (NGT) was established under:',
opts:['Environment Protection Act 1986 directly','NGT Act 2010 — specialized court for civil environmental cases, with power to award compensation and order remediation','Wildlife Protection Act 1972','Forest Conservation Act 1980'],
ans:1,
explain:'NGT Act 2010: Specialized tribunal. Original + appellate jurisdiction for environmental cases. Can award compensation for environmental damage, impose penalties, order cleanup. Appeal to Supreme Court.',
wrongExplain:'NGT handles: Ganga/Yamuna pollution, Delhi smog, CRZ violations, mining cases. Replaced HC environment benches. Principal bench in Delhi, zonal benches in Chennai, Pune, Bhopal, Kolkata.'},

{id:'q3_ev_013',subject:'Environment',node:'ev3',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'ABS',
q:'Nagoya Protocol (under CBD) mandates:',
opts:['Free global access to all genetic resources','Prior Informed Consent of provider country + fair benefit sharing with communities holding traditional knowledge','No regulation on biodiversity access','Only marine genetic resources regulation'],
ans:1,
explain:'Nagoya Protocol (2010): ABS framework. Companies using traditional knowledge (Neem, turmeric, Darjeeling tea) must seek prior informed consent and share benefits with source communities.',
wrongExplain:'India\'s Biological Diversity Act 2002: National Biodiversity Authority (Chennai) regulates access. National Biodiversity Fund. India led global push for ABS after biopiracy cases.'},

{id:'q3_ev_014',subject:'Environment',node:'ev2',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Carbon Markets',
q:'Article 6 of the Paris Agreement establishes:',
opts:['Climate finance obligations of developed nations','Voluntary cooperative mechanisms including bilateral carbon trading (6.2), new UN carbon market (6.4), and non-market approaches (6.8)','Loss and Damage Fund provisions','Adaptation planning requirements'],
ans:1,
explain:'Art 6: Voluntary carbon markets. Art 6.2 = bilateral country-to-country carbon credit trading. Art 6.4 = new UN-supervised carbon market replacing Kyoto\'s CDM. COP26 Glasgow finally agreed on rules.',
wrongExplain:'CDM (Clean Development Mechanism under Kyoto) = expired. Art 6.4 is its successor. Carbon credits from developing countries offset developed country emissions. COP29 finalised Article 6 operationalization.'},

{id:'q3_ev_015',subject:'Environment',node:'ev1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Edge Effect',
q:'The "Edge Effect" in ecology means:',
opts:['Pollution concentrated near industrial boundaries','Higher species diversity at ecotones — boundaries between two different ecosystems','Only species decline at forest edges','Coastal erosion at land-sea boundaries'],
ans:1,
explain:'Edge Effect: Ecotone (transition zone between two ecosystems) has higher biodiversity — species from both ecosystems plus specialist edge species. However, forest fragments also have vulnerable edges susceptible to invasives.',
wrongExplain:'Forest fragmentation creates too many edges — bad for interior forest species. Edge effect = more species at natural ecotones. But fragmented forest edges = threat. Both sides tested in UPSC.'},

{id:'q3_ev_016',subject:'Environment',node:'ev4',difficulty:'medium',year:2022,topic:'E-Waste',
q:'India\'s rank as an e-waste generator is:',
opts:['1st globally','3rd largest globally (after USA and China)','5th globally','Not significant globally'],
ans:1,
explain:'India = 3rd largest e-waste generator globally. E-Waste (Management) Rules 2022 under EPA 1986: Extended Producer Responsibility. India generates ~3.2 million metric tonnes annually.',
wrongExplain:'E-waste contains hazardous: lead, mercury, cadmium, arsenic. Informal sector recycling = toxic leaching into soil/water. Formal recycling mandatory but compliance is low.'},

{id:'q3_ev_017',subject:'Environment',node:'ev5',difficulty:'hard',year:2020,topic:'Nuclear',
q:'India\'s three-stage nuclear programme was designed by:',
opts:['Vikram Sarabhai','Homi J. Bhabha — uses India\'s abundant thorium reserves in the final stage','APJ Abdul Kalam','Raja Ramanna'],
ans:1,
explain:'Bhabha\'s three stages: Stage 1 = PHWRs using natural uranium (operational). Stage 2 = Fast Breeder Reactors using plutonium from Stage 1 (PFBR at Kalpakkam nearing completion). Stage 3 = Thorium reactors. India has 25% of world\'s thorium.',
wrongExplain:'India not in NPT (Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty). India-US Nuclear Deal (2008) lifted technology sanctions. India = 7 operational nuclear power plants. The three-stage logic: limited uranium → breed plutonium → switch to thorium.'},

{id:'q3_ev_018',subject:'Environment',node:'ev2',difficulty:'medium',year:2023,topic:'IPCC',
q:'IPCC (Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change) was jointly established by:',
opts:['UNEP alone in 1985','WMO and UNEP jointly in 1988','UN General Assembly in 2000','UNFCCC in 1994'],
ans:1,
explain:'IPCC established 1988 by WMO + UNEP. Does not conduct original research — synthesizes peer-reviewed scientific literature. IPCC AR6 (2021-22) = strongest statement: human influence is "unequivocal" cause of climate change.',
wrongExplain:'3 IPCC Working Groups: WG1 (Physical Science Basis), WG2 (Impacts, Adaptation, Vulnerability), WG3 (Mitigation of Climate Change). Synthesis Report = final summary. Member states approve Summary for Policymakers.'},

{id:'q3_ev_019',subject:'Environment',node:'ev3',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'Protected Areas',
q:'A Tiger Reserve is different from a National Park because:',
opts:['They are identical in legal protection','Tiger Reserve = larger designated area with Core (strictly protected) + Buffer zone (limited human activity). National Park = strictly protected throughout','Tiger Reserve is stricter than NP','National Parks have buffer zones, Tiger Reserves do not'],
ans:1,
explain:'Tiger Reserve: Core (may include National Park/WLS) + Buffer (limited eco-tourism, community activities). Designated by NTCA under WPA. Tiger Reserve can be 1,000+ sq km total.',
wrongExplain:'Hierarchy of protection: National Park > Wildlife Sanctuary > Conservation Reserve > Community Reserve. Tiger Reserve is not a separate category under WPA — it is a management designation over existing NP/WLS.'},

{id:'q3_ev_020',subject:'Environment',node:'ev4',difficulty:'hard',year:2021,topic:'Conventions',
q:'The Basel Convention (1989) deals with:',
opts:['Marine pollution from ships (MARPOL)','Transboundary movement of hazardous wastes — prevents developed nations dumping hazardous waste in developing nations','Air pollution from industry','Chemical weapons destruction'],
ans:1,
explain:'Basel Convention: Controls export of hazardous wastes. 2019 amendment added plastic waste to controlled substances. India is a party. Prevents "waste colonialism."',
wrongExplain:'RSB trio to remember: Rotterdam Convention (Prior Informed Consent for hazardous chemicals trade), Stockholm Convention (POPs), Basel Convention (hazardous waste movement). MARPOL = separate maritime pollution treaty.'},

{id:'q3_ev_021',subject:'Environment',node:'ev1',difficulty:'basic',year:2020,topic:'Biodiversity Hotspots',
q:'How many of the 36 global biodiversity hotspots are in India?',
opts:['1 (Western Ghats)','3 (Western Ghats, Eastern Himalayas, Indo-Burma)','5','2 (Western Ghats and Eastern Himalayas only)'],
ans:1,
explain:'India has 3 biodiversity hotspots: (1) Western Ghats, (2) Eastern Himalayas, (3) Indo-Burma (includes NE India + Myanmar). Criteria: >1,500 endemic plant species + >70% habitat already lost.',
wrongExplain:'Western Ghats: 5,000+ flowering plants, 1,700+ endemic. Eastern Himalayas: highest bird diversity in India. Indo-Burma: rich freshwater biodiversity. All three face deforestation and development pressure.'},

{id:'q3_ev_022',subject:'Environment',node:'ev6',difficulty:'medium',year:2022,topic:'CRZ',
q:'Coastal Regulation Zone (CRZ) notification regulates activities within:',
opts:['500m from High Tide Line (HTL) on the landward side + the intertidal zone between HTL and Low Tide Line','Only port and harbour areas','100m from shoreline','Only industrial coastal zones'],
ans:0,
explain:'CRZ 2019 Notification: Regulates land within 500m from HTL (High Tide Line). Zones: CRZ-I (ecologically sensitive — mangroves, coral, sand dunes), CRZ-II (built-up municipal areas), CRZ-III (rural), CRZ-IV (islands).',
wrongExplain:'CRZ-I has maximum protection — no construction. CRZ notifications revised in 1991, 2011, 2019. Fishermen\'s rights provisions repeatedly contested. MoEFCC manages CRZ.'},

{id:'q3_ev_023',subject:'Environment',node:'ev5',difficulty:'medium',year:2023,topic:'Biofuels',
q:'India achieved 20% ethanol blending in petrol:',
opts:['By 2021 as originally targeted','In 2024 — ahead of the 2025-26 target set under National Policy on Biofuels 2018','By 2030 only','This target has not been achieved yet'],
ans:1,
explain:'India achieved 20% ethanol blending milestone in 2024 ahead of the 2025-26 target. Sources: sugarcane molasses, damaged grains, surplus rice. Reduces oil import bill and supports farmers.',
wrongExplain:'India achieved 10% blending in 2022 and 20% in 2024. E20 (20% ethanol in petrol) reduces CO2 emissions per litre. Maharashtra and UP are major ethanol-producing states.'},

{id:'q3_ev_024',subject:'Environment',node:'ev4',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'Ocean Acidification',
q:'Ocean acidification occurs because:',
opts:['Industrial effluents directly acidify oceans','Oceans absorb ~25-30% of atmospheric CO2 which forms carbonic acid — ocean pH has fallen ~0.1 units since industrialization (30% more acidic on H+ scale)','Sea surface temperature rise alone acidifies','Nuclear testing releases acidic compounds'],
ans:1,
explain:'CO2 + H2O → H2CO3 (carbonic acid) → lower ocean pH. Since industrial revolution, ocean pH: 8.2 → ~8.1. Dissolves calcium carbonate shells/skeletons of corals, oysters, sea urchins, pteropods.',
wrongExplain:'Combined threat: ocean warming + acidification for coral reefs. Great Barrier Reef has experienced mass bleaching. Coral Triangle (SE Asia) = global coral biodiversity centre under threat.'},

{id:'q3_ev_025',subject:'Environment',node:'ev1',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'Mangroves',
q:'Mangroves are found in:',
opts:['Deep freshwater lakes','Coastal intertidal zones — interface of land and sea in tropical and subtropical regions','Alpine meadows above 3000m','Semi-arid desert fringes'],
ans:1,
explain:'Mangroves = salt-tolerant forests in intertidal zones. India: Sundarbans (West Bengal, largest), Bhitarkanika (Odisha), Gulf of Kutch (Gujarat), Andaman & Nicobar. Provide coastal protection + blue carbon sequestration.',
wrongExplain:'India has ~3% of world\'s mangroves. Sundarbans = Ramsar site + UNESCO WHS + Biosphere Reserve + Tiger Reserve. Mangroves sequester carbon 3-5x more than tropical forests — "blue carbon."'},

