{id:'q3_h_001',subject:'History',node:'h1',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'Sangam Age',
q:'The Sangam Age of South India (300 BCE – 300 CE) is known for:',
opts:['Vedic rituals and Sanskrit literature exclusively','Tamil literature (Purananuru, Akananuru) + three Tamil kingdoms (Chera, Chola, Pandya) + trade with Rome','Buddhist monasteries dominating South India','Mughal administrative practices in South'],
ans:1,
explain:'Sangam Age: Three Tamil kingdoms. Sangam = assembly of Tamil poets. Earliest Tamil literature. Roman trade: Arikamedu (Pondicherry) = archaeological evidence with Roman amphora, coins.',
wrongExplain:'Sangam literature predates Mughal era by 1,500+ years. Tamil Bhakti (Alvars, Nayanars) came later (6th-9th century CE). Sangam poems describe war, love, royal courts in vivid detail.'},

{id:'q3_h_002',subject:'History',node:'h1',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'Gupta Empire',
q:'The Gupta Period is called the "Golden Age" of India because of:',
opts:['Largest territorial expansion in Indian history','Unparalleled achievements in science, literature, and arts: Kalidasa, Aryabhata, Varahamihira, Sushruta','Strict religious uniformity enforced by state','Military domination of all of Asia'],
ans:1,
explain:'Gupta Period (4th-6th century CE): Kalidasa (Shakuntalam, Meghaduta), Aryabhata (zero, Earth rotation, pi), Varahamihira (astronomy), Sushruta (surgery). Peak under Chandragupta II (Vikramaditya).',
wrongExplain:'Fa Hien (Chinese traveler) visited during Gupta period and described prosperous, tolerant society. Decline due to Huna (White Hun) invasions in 5th century CE.'},

{id:'q3_h_003',subject:'History',node:'h2',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Bhakti Movement',
q:'The North Indian Bhakti Movement (14th-16th century) was characterized by:',
opts:['Strict caste hierarchy reinforced through religion','Personal devotion to God, rejection of caste distinctions, use of vernacular languages (Awadhi, Braj, Hindi)','Arabic and Persian as the only religious languages','Exclusively royal patronage and elite participation'],
ans:1,
explain:'Bhakti: Kabir (weaver, criticized Hindu + Muslim orthodoxy), Mirabai (Rajput princess, Krishna devotee), Tulsidas (Ramcharitmanas in Awadhi), Surdas. Made religion accessible to common people.',
wrongExplain:'Bhakti had two branches: Saguna (God with form — Tulsidas, Surdas) and Nirguna (formless God — Kabir, Namdev). Social reform dimension: all castes could participate in devotion.'},

{id:'q3_h_004',subject:'History',node:'h2',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'Mughal Administration',
q:'The Mansabdari system under Akbar was:',
opts:['A land grant system for temple endowments','A numerical rank system for military and civil officials — determined salary, troops to maintain, and court status','A peasant taxation system based on land area','Trade guild organization by Emperor'],
ans:1,
explain:'Mansabdari: Ranks (mansab) from 10 to 5,000+. Two components: Zat (personal rank, determines salary) and Sawar (cavalry to be maintained). Officials paid in cash or jagirs (temporary land revenue assignments).',
wrongExplain:'Key: Mansabdars did NOT own land — jagirs were temporary and transferable. Solved the hereditary feudal lord problem. Abu\'l Fazl described it in Ain-i-Akbari in detail.'},

{id:'q3_h_005',subject:'History',node:'h3',difficulty:'hard',year:2020,topic:'Lucknow Pact',
q:'The Lucknow Pact (1916) was historically significant because:',
opts:['It led to the formal founding of the INC','INC and Muslim League jointly demanded constitutional reforms for the first time — high-water mark of Hindu-Muslim political unity','It established Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms','It was Gandhi\'s first political achievement in India'],
ans:1,
explain:'Lucknow Pact (December 1916): Signed by Tilak (INC) and Jinnah (Muslim League). Joint constitutional demands. INC accepted separate electorates. Unprecedented Hindu-Muslim political unity before Gandhi era.',
wrongExplain:'Context: Tilak united Extremists and Moderates within INC. Jinnah was then a secular nationalist. The pact\'s unity broke down later. Montagu-Chelmsford Report (1918) followed separately.'},

{id:'q3_h_006',subject:'History',node:'h3',difficulty:'medium',year:2023,topic:'Rowlatt Act',
q:'The Rowlatt Act (1919) provoked mass protests because:',
opts:['It imposed heavy new taxes on Indians','It allowed detention without trial and trial without jury for political cases — called "Black Act": no vakil, no daleel, no appeal','It partitioned the Punjab province','It banned the Indian National Congress'],
ans:1,
explain:'Rowlatt Act: Extended wartime emergency powers — imprisonment without trial for suspected seditionists. Gandhi called for hartal (strike). Led to Jallianwala Bagh massacre (April 13, 1919) — General Dyer ordered firing, 379+ killed.',
wrongExplain:'Jallianwala Bagh turned moderate Indians permanently against British. Hunter Commission report whitewashed Dyer. British response radicalized the independence movement significantly.'},

{id:'q3_h_007',subject:'History',node:'h3',difficulty:'hard',year:2021,topic:'Champaran',
q:'The Champaran Satyagraha (1917) was about:',
opts:['Textile workers in Ahmedabad fighting for wages','Indigo cultivators in Bihar forced to grow indigo on 3/20 of their land at fixed prices for British planters (Tinkathia system)','Gandhi\'s first salt protest','Civil disobedience against local body taxation'],
ans:1,
explain:'Champaran (1917): Tinkathia system forced farmers to cultivate indigo (instead of food crops) and sell at fixed low prices to British planters. Gandhi investigated, organized resistance. First successful Satyagraha in India.',
wrongExplain:'Champaran Commission (1917) followed — Tinkathia abolished. This established Gandhi\'s method: fact-finding + local mobilization + civil resistance. Rajendra Prasad was Gandhi\'s associate here.'},

{id:'q3_h_008',subject:'History',node:'h3',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'August Offer',
q:'The August Offer (1940) was rejected by the INC because:',
opts:['It offered too much power to Congress immediately','It promised dominion status only after WWII with no immediate power-sharing — Congress wanted immediate responsible government','It divided India along religious lines','It fully accepted the Muslim League\'s demands'],
ans:1,
explain:'August Offer (Lord Linlithgow, 1940): Promised expansion of Executive Council + dominion status after WWII. Gandhi called it inadequate. Led to Individual Satyagraha (1940-41).',
wrongExplain:'Jinnah accepted (ML). INC resigned from provinces (1939) after war declared without consulting Indians. Congress demanded immediate steps toward independence. Context of WWII crucial here.'},

{id:'q3_h_009',subject:'History',node:'h4',difficulty:'medium',year:2022,topic:'Civil Services',
q:'"Steel Frame of India" — this phrase used by Sardar Patel referred to:',
opts:['IIT-manufactured steel industry','Indian Administrative Service (IAS) — the permanent civil service providing continuity regardless of political changes','Indian Army\'s structural backbone','Constitutional bodies as a whole'],
ans:1,
explain:'"Steel Frame" term originally used by Lloyd George for the ICS. Patel (Home Minister, 1947) retained civil services post-independence and called the IAS "Steel Frame of India." Ensured administrative continuity.',
wrongExplain:'ICS officers were largely retained as IAS. Patel convinced skeptical Congress leaders who wanted to replace the British-trained service. Turned out to be critical for national integration.'},

{id:'q3_h_010',subject:'History',node:'h4',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Hyderabad Integration',
q:'Operation Polo (September 1948) refers to:',
opts:['India\'s first satellite launch attempt','Military police action to integrate Hyderabad into Indian Union — ending the Nizam\'s bid for independence','Evacuation of Indians from Burma','India\'s first military exercise with USA'],
ans:1,
explain:'Operation Polo: Indian Army action against Nizam Mir Osman Ali Khan\'s Hyderabad, which had declared independence. Sardar Patel ordered the "Police Action." Over in 5 days. Last major princely state integration.',
wrongExplain:'Three methods of princely state integration: (1) Junagadh = plebiscite confirmed accession; (2) Kashmir = Instrument of Accession October 1947, dispute continues; (3) Hyderabad = military force September 1948.'},

{id:'q3_h_011',subject:'History',node:'h1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Buddhism',
q:'The Noble Eightfold Path taught by Gautama Buddha comprises:',
opts:['Eight gods of early Vedic tradition','Right View, Right Intention, Right Speech, Right Action, Right Livelihood, Right Effort, Right Mindfulness, Right Concentration — the Middle Way','Eight categories of caste','Eight seasons of the year'],
ans:1,
explain:'Eightfold Path = Middle Way between extreme asceticism and indulgence. Buddha\'s First Sermon at Sarnath (Dhammachakrapavattana = Turning of the Wheel of Dharma) taught this.',
wrongExplain:'Jainism = Three Jewels (right faith, right knowledge, right conduct) + five vows. Buddhism = Four Noble Truths + Eightfold Path. Key distinction for UPSC ancient India questions.'},

{id:'q3_h_012',subject:'History',node:'h2',difficulty:'hard',year:2020,topic:'Alauddin Khilji',
q:'Alauddin Khilji\'s market control system involved:',
opts:['Free market pricing for all goods','Four regulated markets with fixed prices, government controllers and spies to prevent profiteering — funded his massive army cheaply','Only food price controls','Royal monopoly on all trade'],
ans:1,
explain:'Alauddin\'s four markets: grain, cattle, cloth, general commodities. Diwan-i-Riyasat controlled prices. Spies enforced rules. Purpose: maintain large army cheaply. Barani (historian) described this extraordinary experiment.',
wrongExplain:'Market controls ended with Alauddin\'s death — system depended on his strong administration. Showed a medieval ruler\'s attempt at planned economy. Remarkable administrative achievement of its era.'},

{id:'q3_h_013',subject:'History',node:'h3',difficulty:'medium',year:2022,topic:'Wardha Scheme',
q:'Wardha Scheme of Basic Education (Nai Talim, 1937) was associated with:',
opts:['B.R. Ambedkar','Jawaharlal Nehru','Mahatma Gandhi — education through productive craft activity','Rabindranath Tagore\'s Shantiniketan'],
ans:2,
explain:'Wardha/Nai Talim: Gandhi\'s educational philosophy — learning through craft (spinning, weaving, agriculture). Mother tongue instruction. "Education of hands, heart and head." Self-sufficient schools.',
wrongExplain:'Tagore\'s Shantiniketan = nature-based, arts-integrated education. Gandhi\'s Nai Talim = craft-based, self-sufficient school. Both opposed colonial rote-learning model but with different approaches.'},

{id:'q3_h_014',subject:'History',node:'h4',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'Green Revolution',
q:'India\'s Green Revolution was achieved through:',
opts:['Land redistribution to farmers','High Yielding Variety (HYV) seeds + irrigation + fertilizers, primarily in Punjab, Haryana, Western UP — led by M.S. Swaminathan and Norman Borlaug','Government ownership of farms','Traditional farming improvement programs'],
ans:1,
explain:'Green Revolution (1960s-70s): HYV wheat/rice + irrigation + chemical fertilizers. India went from chronic food deficit to food surplus. Norman Borlaug = Nobel Peace Prize 1970. M.S. Swaminathan = Father of Green Revolution in India.',
wrongExplain:'Geographically concentrated: Punjab, Haryana, Western UP. Created regional imbalance — South and Eastern India largely excluded initially. Evergreen Revolution concept (Swaminathan) = sustainable intensification.'},

{id:'q3_h_015',subject:'History',node:'h3',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Mountbatten Plan',
q:'The Mountbatten Plan (June 3, 1947) provided for:',
opts:['United India with dominion status','Partition into India and Pakistan as separate dominions + Boundary Commission (Radcliffe) to divide Punjab and Bengal','Federation of all princely states','Gradual transfer of power over 10 years'],
ans:1,
explain:'Mountbatten Plan: Partition into India (August 15) and Pakistan (August 14) as dominions. Cyril Radcliffe\'s Boundary Commission divided Punjab and Bengal. Princely states given choice of accession.',
wrongExplain:'Cabinet Mission Plan (1946) had proposed united India with three-tier federation. Both INC and ML eventually accepted partition. Radcliffe Award announced August 17 — after independence — to prevent pre-announcement violence.'},

{id:'q3_h_016',subject:'History',node:'h1',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'Maurya Art',
q:'Mathura School of Art (Kushana period) was characterized by:',
opts:['Heavy Persian artistic influence','Indigenous Indian tradition — depicted Buddha with Indian features, local red sandstone, no Hellenistic drapery','Central Asian art styles dominant','Only royal portraits, no religious subjects'],
ans:1,
explain:'Mathura Art (1st-4th century CE): Indigenous style. Used spotted red sandstone. Early Buddha images without halo. Bodhisattva images prominent. Contrast: Gandhara School = Greek-influenced (heavy drapery, Apollo-like Buddha).',
wrongExplain:'Gandhara (Pakistan/Afghanistan): Hellenistic influence post-Alexander. Mathura: indigenous Indian. Amaravati (Andhra Pradesh): third major school. All three flourished under Kushana patronage.'},

{id:'q3_h_017',subject:'History',node:'h3',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Lahore Resolution',
q:'The Lahore Resolution (1940) by the Muslim League demanded:',
opts:['Independence within a united India','Separate states for Muslim-majority areas in the northwest and east of India — basis of the Pakistan movement','Equal representation in Viceroy\'s Council only','Religious autonomy within undivided India'],
ans:1,
explain:'Lahore Resolution (March 23, 1940 — Pakistan Day): ML demanded "independent states" for Muslim-majority areas. Jinnah\'s Two-Nation Theory. Note: used "states" (plural) initially, later amended to "state."',
wrongExplain:'Lahore Resolution did not explicitly use the word "Pakistan" — that was Choudhry Rahmat Ali\'s 1933 pamphlet. Allama Iqbal (1930) gave philosophical foundation for separate Muslim state.'},

{id:'q3_h_018',subject:'History',node:'h2',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'Sikhism',
q:'Guru Nanak Dev Ji founded Sikhism emphasizing:',
opts:['Anti-Mughal resistance as primary teaching','One God (Ik Onkar), equality of all people, rejection of caste and idol worship, direct devotion without rituals or intermediaries','Buddhist revival in Punjab','Opposition to Bhakti movement traditions'],
ans:1,
explain:'Guru Nanak (1469-1539): Ik Onkar (One God), Naam Japna (meditation), Kirat Karo (honest work), Vand Chakko (share with others). Rejected caste, pilgrimage, idol worship. Ten Gurus. Guru Granth Sahib = eternal living Guru.',
wrongExplain:'Sikhism is a distinct religion, not a sect of Hinduism or Islam. Guru Gobind Singh (10th Guru) created Khalsa (1699). Guru Arjan Dev (5th Guru) compiled Adi Granth and built Golden Temple.'},

{id:'q3_h_019',subject:'History',node:'h4',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'First Five Year Plan',
q:'India\'s First Five Year Plan (1951-56) prioritized:',
opts:['Heavy industry and steel plants','Agriculture and irrigation — to address food shortage left by Partition and war, using Harrod-Domar model','Defense manufacturing','Export-led growth'],
ans:1,
explain:'First Plan: Priority to agriculture, irrigation, community development, power (Bhakra Nangal dam). Used Harrod-Domar model. Succeeded — grew 3.6% vs target 2.1%. Established planning as India\'s development approach.',
wrongExplain:'Second Plan (1956-61) = Mahalanobis model — heavy industry first (Bhilai, Rourkela, Durgapur steel plants). First Plan: food security. Second Plan: industrial base. Logical sequencing.'},

{id:'q3_h_020',subject:'History',node:'h1',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Indus Valley',
q:'The Indus Valley Civilization was contemporary with:',
opts:['Roman and Greek civilizations','Mesopotamian civilization (Sumerians) and Ancient Egypt — all flourished around 2600-1900 BCE','Chinese Han Dynasty','Persian Achaemenid Empire'],
ans:1,
explain:'Harappan Civilization (2600-1900 BCE): Contemporary with Sumer/Babylon and Egypt (Old Kingdom). Trade confirmed: Harappan seals found at Ur (Iraq), cuneiform tablets mention "Meluhha" (likely Harappa).',
wrongExplain:'Roman = 500 BCE-476 CE. Achaemenid = 550-330 BCE. Han Dynasty = 206 BCE-220 CE. All much later than Harappa. Contemporaneous civilizations help date Harappan civilization.'},

{id:'q3_h_021',subject:'History',node:'h3',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'Simon Commission',
q:'The Simon Commission (1927-29) was boycotted by Indians because:',
opts:['It was too expensive to host','It had no Indian member — an all-British commission reviewing constitutional reforms affecting India\'s future (\'Simon Go Back\')','It proposed partition of India','It raised taxes on Indians'],
ans:1,
explain:'"Simon Go Back" movement. Lala Lajpat Rai led protest at Lahore — was lathi-charged and died in November 1928. INC response: Nehru Report (1928) as Indian alternative.',
wrongExplain:'Nehru Report (1928): Proposed Dominion Status + Common electorate (rejecting separate electorates). Jinnah\'s amendments rejected → Hindu-Muslim rift began widening.'},

{id:'q3_h_022',subject:'History',node:'h2',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Maratha Empire',
q:'The Maratha Confederacy after Shivaji was characterized by:',
opts:['Strict centralized monarchy continuing Shivaji\'s model','Loose confederation of chiefs (Holkar, Scindias, Bhonsle, Gaikwad) with Peshwa as de facto head, reaching peak under Peshwa Baji Rao I','Alliance with Mughal emperors','Rapid territorial shrinkage after Shivaji\'s death'],
ans:1,
explain:'Post-Shivaji: Peshwas (Brahmin ministers) became effective rulers. Peak under Peshwa Baji Rao I (1720-40) — empire stretched from Peshawar to Bengal. Third Battle of Panipat (1761) = devastating loss to Ahmad Shah Abdali.',
wrongExplain:'Panipat 1761 ended Maratha bid for pan-India empire. British exploited the subsequent power vacuum. Peshwa power never recovered. Bajirao II surrendered to British in 1818.'},

{id:'q3_h_023',subject:'History',node:'h3',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'Cripps Mission',
q:'The Cripps Mission (1942) failed primarily because:',
opts:['It proposed immediate full independence','INC rejected it — offered dominion status only after WWII with no immediate power transfer or Indian control of defence; Gandhi called it a "post-dated cheque on a failing bank"','It was too expensive for India','It proposed Hindu-majority government'],
ans:1,
explain:'Cripps Mission (Sir Stafford Cripps): Offered constituent assembly + dominion status after WWII + right to secede. INC wanted immediate independence + defence portfolio. Jinnah rejected too. Led to Quit India Movement (August 1942).',
wrongExplain:'Churchill reportedly sabotaged Cripps Mission behind the scenes. The failure of every negotiated solution pushed Gandhi toward the more confrontational Quit India approach.'},

{id:'q3_h_024',subject:'History',node:'h1',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'Ahimsa',
q:'The principle of "Ahimsa" as an absolute philosophical commitment was most systematically developed by:',
opts:['Early Vedic tradition mainly','Jainism — extending ahimsa to all living beings in thought, word, and deed','Buddhism exclusively','The Bhakti saints of medieval India'],
ans:1,
explain:'Ahimsa in Jainism: Not harming any living being (including insects) in thought, word, action. Most absolute formulation. Influenced Gandhi\'s Satyagraha. Buddhism also emphasizes ahimsa but Jainism is most absolute.',
wrongExplain:'Jain monks wear masks to avoid breathing insects. Digambara Jains sweep path before walking. This absolute ahimsa is distinctly Jain. Gandhi cited Jainism (and Tolstoy) as influences for his political method.'},

{id:'q3_h_025',subject:'History',node:'h4',difficulty:'medium',year:2023,topic:'Emergency 1975',
q:'The Emergency (1975-77) was proclaimed under:',
opts:['Article 356 only (President Rule)','Article 352 (National Emergency) on grounds of "internal disturbance" — India\'s most controversial Emergency in history','Presidential discretionary power','Joint Parliamentary Resolution'],
ans:1,
explain:'Emergency (June 25, 1975 – March 21, 1977): PM Indira Gandhi invoked Art 352. Art 19 FRs suspended, press censored, opposition leaders imprisoned (JP Narayan). 42nd Amendment rushed through. Revoked after 1977 election defeat.',
wrongExplain:'After Emergency: 44th Amendment changed "internal disturbance" to "armed rebellion" (harder to invoke). 1977 Janata Party victory = peoples\' verdict against Emergency. Considered India\'s darkest chapter.'},

