{id:'q3_g_001',subject:'Geography',node:'g1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Ring of Fire',
q:'The "Ring of Fire" refers to:',
opts:['A climate zone near the Tropics','The ~40,000 km arc of intense volcanic and seismic activity encircling the Pacific Ocean — 75% of world\'s volcanoes and 90% of earthquakes','The Indian Ocean monsoon belt','Saharan desert wind patterns'],
ans:1,
explain:'Ring of Fire: Pacific Plate subducting under surrounding plates. India\'s Himalayan earthquakes are separate — Indian Plate collision with Eurasian Plate. Andaman-Nicobar islands = part of Ring of Fire.',
wrongExplain:'India\'s seismic zones I-V. Zone V = most hazardous: Himalayan belt, NE India, Andaman. Kutch (Gujarat) had 2001 earthquake (Zone V). Different tectonic cause from Pacific Ring of Fire.'},

{id:'q3_g_002',subject:'Geography',node:'g2',difficulty:'medium',year:2022,topic:'Coriolis Effect',
q:'The Coriolis Effect causes:',
opts:['Ocean tides rising and falling','Deflection of winds and ocean currents to the RIGHT in the Northern Hemisphere and to the LEFT in the Southern Hemisphere due to Earth\'s rotation','Mountain formation through plate tectonics','River erosion and valley formation'],
ans:1,
explain:'Coriolis Effect: Earth\'s rotation causes apparent deflection of moving air/water. In NH: deflects right (anticyclockwise cyclones). In SH: deflects left (clockwise cyclones). Drives trade winds, westerlies, monsoon patterns.',
wrongExplain:'ITCZ + Coriolis = trade wind systems. Indian Monsoon: SW winds driven by pressure difference + Coriolis deflection. Bay of Bengal cyclones rotate counterclockwise in NH.'},

{id:'q3_g_003',subject:'Geography',node:'g2',difficulty:'hard',year:2020,topic:'Peninsular Rivers',
q:'Peninsular rivers of India are characterized by:',
opts:['Youthful stage with gorges and waterfalls throughout','Mature stage with wide valleys; most flow west to east into Bay of Bengal — exceptions: Narmada and Tapi flow west into Arabian Sea','Originating from Himalayas like Indus or Ganga','Large sediment loads equal to Himalayan rivers'],
ans:1,
explain:'Peninsular rivers: Rain-fed (seasonal), mature hard rock courses, older than Himalayas. Most flow W to E into BoB (Krishna, Godavari, Cauvery, Mahanadi). Narmada/Tapi = flow west through rift valleys into Arabian Sea.',
wrongExplain:'Himalayan rivers: Snow-fed (perennial), youthful, high sediment. Narmada flows through the Narmada-Son tectonic rift — hence west direction. This is a frequently tested distinction.'},

{id:'q3_g_004',subject:'Geography',node:'g1',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Himalayan Formation',
q:'The Himalayas were formed by:',
opts:['Volcanic eruptions beneath the ocean floor','Collision of the Indian Plate (moving northward from Gondwana) with the Eurasian Plate starting ~50 million years ago — Tethys Sea sediments folded upward','Gradual erosion revealing underlying rocks','Continental plates separating rather than colliding'],
ans:1,
explain:'Himalayas: Indian plate broke from Gondwana ~200 MYA, drifted north, collided with Eurasian plate ~50 MYA. Tethys Sea sediments folded up. Himalayas still rising ~1-2 cm/year. Indus-Ganga plain = former Tethys Sea floor.',
wrongExplain:'Deccan Traps = volcanic. Himalayas = tectonic folding (convergent plate boundary). Rift valleys like East African Rift = divergent boundaries. Narmada flows through rift valley.'},

{id:'q3_g_005',subject:'Geography',node:'g3',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Demographic Dividend',
q:'India\'s "demographic dividend" refers to:',
opts:['Economic benefit of high birth rates through population growth','Economic growth potential when a large proportion of population is in the working age (15-64) with relatively fewer dependents','Remittances from Indian diaspora overseas','Benefits of population decline in old age'],
ans:1,
explain:'Demographic Dividend: Phase when working-age population is largest relative to dependents. India\'s window: ~2020-2050. Requires jobs + skills for ~900 million working-age people. East Asian Tigers utilized it well.',
wrongExplain:'India\'s median age ~29 years (2024). Missing this window = demographic burden. Key requirements: quality education, skill development (Skill India), job creation (PLI scheme, manufacturing push).'},

{id:'q3_g_006',subject:'Geography',node:'g2',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'Indian Monsoon',
q:'India\'s Southwest Monsoon is driven by:',
opts:['Atlantic Ocean influence on Indian weather','Differential heating of land and sea creating pressure gradient + Coriolis deflection + Tibetan Plateau acting as thermal engine','Arctic polar vortex disruption in summer','El Niño events in the Pacific directly'],
ans:1,
explain:'Indian Monsoon: Land heats faster than ocean → low pressure over South Asia. Moist SW winds rush from Indian Ocean. Tibetan Plateau (heated in summer) creates intense low pressure drawing monsoon northward.',
wrongExplain:'El Niño (warm Pacific) weakens Indian Monsoon. La Niña (cool Pacific) strengthens it. Tibetan Plateau is the unique driver of the Indian monsoon — its heating effect is why India gets such strong monsoon.'},

{id:'q3_g_007',subject:'Geography',node:'g4',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'Minerals',
q:'Odisha\'s importance for India\'s mineral economy is primarily because of:',
opts:['Oil and natural gas reserves offshore','~50% of India\'s iron ore production (Sundargarh, Keonjhar, Mayurbhanj districts) + coal, manganese, bauxite, chromite','Only coal reserves','Mostly agricultural economy, not minerals'],
ans:1,
explain:'Odisha: Largest iron ore producer (~50% of India\'s output). Barbil-Koira-Joda belt in Sundargarh/Keonjhar/Mayurbhanj. Exports via Paradip Port. Also: coal (Ib valley), chromite (world largest), manganese, bauxite.',
wrongExplain:'Jharkhand = coal (Jharia), uranium (Jaduguda), iron ore. Rajasthan = copper (Khetri), zinc (Zawar). Chhattisgarh = coal, iron ore (Bailadila). Odisha specifically = iron ore dominance.'},

{id:'q3_g_008',subject:'Geography',node:'g1',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'Indian Ocean Dipole',
q:'Indian Ocean Dipole (IOD) affects India\'s monsoon by:',
opts:['No significant effect on monsoon','Positive IOD (warmer western Indian Ocean) tends to bring above-normal monsoon rainfall to India; negative IOD = below-normal','Only affecting coastal rainfall, not inland areas','Having identical effect to El Niño'],
ans:1,
explain:'IOD: Sea surface temperature difference between western and eastern Indian Ocean. Positive IOD = warmer western, cooler eastern = more moisture available for Indian monsoon. Interacts with ENSO effects.',
wrongExplain:'IOD and ENSO are separate phenomena. In 2019, positive IOD partially offset El Niño\'s negative effect on Indian monsoon. Both factors used by IMD for monsoon prediction.'},

{id:'q3_g_009',subject:'Geography',node:'g2',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Chilika Lake',
q:'Chilika Lake is ecologically significant as:',
opts:['Largest freshwater lake in India','Largest coastal lagoon in Asia — Ramsar site hosting Irrawaddy dolphins, 340+ bird species, 160+ fish species','India\'s major hydropower reservoir','Saltwater inland lake in Rajasthan'],
ans:1,
explain:'Chilika Lake (Odisha): Largest coastal lagoon in Asia, 2nd largest in world. Ramsar site since 1981. India\'s largest wintering ground for migratory birds. Irrawaddy dolphins. Adjacent to Puri and Konark.',
wrongExplain:'Wular Lake (J&K) = largest freshwater lake in India. Loktak (Manipur) = largest freshwater lake in NE India (has floating NP Keibul Lamjao). Chilika = brackish lagoon (coastal, not inland).'},

{id:'q3_g_010',subject:'Geography',node:'g1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Laterite Soil',
q:'Laterite soils are formed in areas with:',
opts:['Cold dry climate with low rainfall','High temperature and heavy seasonal rainfall — intense leaching removes silica and nutrients, leaving iron and aluminium oxides','Semi-arid Deccan Plateau conditions','Alluvial deposition by rivers'],
ans:1,
explain:'Laterite: High rainfall (>200 cm) + high temperature = intense leaching. Iron/aluminium oxides remain → red color. Found in: Western Ghats, NE India, Kerala, Odisha, parts of Karnataka. Good for plantation crops (tea, coffee, rubber, cashew).',
wrongExplain:'Alluvial = Gangetic plains (most fertile). Black (regur) = Deccan Trap (cotton). Red soil = low-rainfall crystalline rocks. Laterite = too much rain + heat = nutrient-poor but good drainage.'},

{id:'q3_g_011',subject:'Geography',node:'g2',difficulty:'medium',year:2022,topic:'Brahmaputra',
q:'The Brahmaputra carries one of the world\'s highest sediment loads because:',
opts:['It flows through soft alluvial plains only','It crosses tectonically active, geologically young, easily erodible Himalayan zone — rainfall + seismic activity + steep gradients maximize erosion','It is the longest river in Asia','It receives the most tributaries'],
ans:1,
explain:'Brahmaputra: Gorge through Namcha Barwa (world\'s largest gorge). Geologically young Himalayas are soft and easily eroded. High rainfall + steep gradient + earthquakes = massive sediment. Creates Majuli island (world\'s largest river island).',
wrongExplain:'Majuli island (Assam) is shrinking due to Brahmaputra\'s erosion and braiding. Annual floods deposit sediment but also erode banks. Brahmaputra floodplain has >100 channel shifts recorded.'},

{id:'q3_g_012',subject:'Geography',node:'g3',difficulty:'hard',year:2020,topic:'Human Development',
q:'India\'s human development "North-South divide" refers to:',
opts:['A purely climate-based division of India','Southern states generally having better HDI indicators (literacy, IMR, life expectancy) vs northern states — reflecting historical social reform differences','Difference in economic size only','Religious composition differences'],
ans:1,
explain:'South India (Kerala, Tamil Nadu, AP, Karnataka) = consistently better literacy, lower IMR, better sex ratio. Historical factors: SNDP movement, Christian missionary education, Dravidian social reform movements.',
wrongExplain:'Kerala = highest literacy + lowest IMR. Bihar = lowest HDI. This reflects: colonial history, social reform movements, public health investment, women\'s empowerment efforts in South vs North.'},

{id:'q3_g_013',subject:'Geography',node:'g2',difficulty:'medium',year:2023,topic:'Black Soil',
q:'Black cotton soil (Regur) is most suitable for cotton because:',
opts:['It has the highest nutrient content of any Indian soil','It retains moisture for long periods (high clay content, self-mulching) and is rich in calcium carbonate — ideal for cotton despite less rainfall in Deccan','It has the best drainage','It is found only where cotton has always grown historically'],
ans:1,
explain:'Regur: High clay → retains moisture. Swells when wet, shrinks/cracks when dry (self-ploughing). Rich in Ca, Mg, Al. Found in: Maharashtra, Madhya Pradesh, Gujarat, Andhra Pradesh, Karnataka. Cotton, jowar, linseed thrive.',
wrongExplain:'Alluvial soils have more nutrients but may waterlog. Regur\'s advantage: moisture retention allows cotton cultivation in low-rainfall Deccan. Self-ploughing (cracks admit water) is unique characteristic.'},

{id:'q3_g_014',subject:'Geography',node:'g4',difficulty:'hard',year:2021,topic:'Punjab Agriculture',
q:'Punjab\'s contribution to India\'s food security disproportionate to its small size is due to:',
opts:['Largest state by area in India','Intensive cultivation of wheat and rice using HYV seeds + canal irrigation + tubewells + full mechanization — Green Revolution epicentre','Oldest farming tradition in India','Richest alluvial soil in the country'],
ans:1,
explain:'Punjab contributes ~30% of wheat and ~12% of rice to the national food pool despite being one of India\'s smallest states. Bhakra dam canals + tubewells + HYV seeds + mechanization = highest productivity.',
wrongExplain:'Punjab now facing: groundwater depletion (tubewells over-exploiting aquifer), soil degradation, crop diversification needed, stubble burning. The Green Revolution success created long-term sustainability challenges.'},

{id:'q3_g_015',subject:'Geography',node:'g1',difficulty:'medium',year:2022,topic:'Tropic of Cancer',
q:'The Tropic of Cancer passes through how many Indian states?',
opts:['6 states','8 states: Gujarat, Rajasthan, MP, Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand, West Bengal, Tripura, Mizoram','10 states','5 states and 2 UTs'],
ans:1,
explain:'Tropic of Cancer (23.5°N) passes through 8 states: Gujarat → Rajasthan → MP → Chhattisgarh → Jharkhand → West Bengal → Tripura → Mizoram. Divides India into tropical (south) and subtropical (north).',
wrongExplain:'Standard Meridian of India = 82°30\'E (through Mirzapur, UP). IST = UTC+5:30. Equator does not pass through India. Tropic of Cancer through 8 states is standard UPSC geography question.'},

{id:'q3_g_016',subject:'Geography',node:'g2',difficulty:'hard',year:2020,topic:'Floods',
q:'India\'s most flood-prone river system is considered to be:',
opts:['The Indus river system','The Brahmaputra — due to highest discharge volume, seismic course changes, massive silt load raising riverbed, and flat Assam plains','The Godavari-Krishna system','The Ganga in its upper course'],
ans:1,
explain:'Brahmaputra: Combination of factors makes it worst for flooding — highest water volume, seismic zone (course can shift suddenly), massive silt raising riverbed, flat plains. Annual floods affect 3+ million in Assam.',
wrongExplain:'Kosi river (Bihar) = "Sorrow of Bihar" — changes course frequently. But Brahmaputra system overall = most complex due to seismic factors. River course shifted significantly after 1950 Assam earthquake.'},

{id:'q3_g_017',subject:'Geography',node:'g3',difficulty:'medium',year:2023,topic:'Urbanization',
q:'India\'s urban population as a percentage of total population (2024 estimate) is approximately:',
opts:['20%','35-36%','50%','60%'],
ans:1,
explain:'India\'s urbanization rate ~35-36% (2024). Compared to China (~65%), USA (~83%), global average (~57%). India is urbanizing rapidly but is still predominantly rural. Urban India contributes ~63% of GDP.',
wrongExplain:'Smart Cities Mission (100 cities), AMRUT (500 cities), PMAY-Urban = major urban development schemes. India will add ~400 million urban residents by 2050 — largest urban transition in history.'},

{id:'q3_g_018',subject:'Geography',node:'g1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'El Nino',
q:'El Niño refers to:',
opts:['A monsoon depression in Bay of Bengal','Abnormal warming of central and eastern Pacific Ocean surface waters occurring every 2-7 years — disrupts global weather patterns including Indian monsoon','Warming of Indian Ocean only','Arctic sea ice melting event'],
ans:1,
explain:'El Niño (Spanish: little boy): Warm Pacific episode. Weakens Indian Monsoon (below normal rainfall). La Niña (cool Pacific) = strengthens monsoon. ENSO cycle affects agriculture, hydropower across India.',
wrongExplain:'IOD (Indian Ocean Dipole) is a separate, distinct phenomenon. IMD forecasts: El Niño year = drought risk. La Niña year = flood risk. 2023 = El Niño year, India had below-normal monsoon in some regions.'},

{id:'q3_g_019',subject:'Geography',node:'g2',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'Jute Cultivation',
q:'Jute cultivation is concentrated in West Bengal because:',
opts:['Government policy directs farmers to grow jute only in West Bengal','Riverine alluvial delta + warm humid climate (>25°C, 150-200 cm rainfall) + standing water for retting — ideal conditions','Cheaper labor compared to other states','Historical accident with no geographic basis'],
ans:1,
explain:'Jute requires: 25-35°C temperature, 150-200 cm rainfall, standing water for retting (decomposing stalks to extract fibers). Ganga-Brahmaputra delta provides perfect conditions. West Bengal = ~80% of India\'s jute.',
wrongExplain:'India = world\'s largest jute producer. Bangladesh also major producer. Jute = "Golden Fiber." Uses: gunny bags, carpet backing. Synthetic fiber competition reduced demand but eco-packaging trend reviving it.'},

{id:'q3_g_020',subject:'Geography',node:'g4',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'Jharkhand Minerals',
q:'Jharkhand is called the "Ruhr of India" because:',
opts:['It has the best climate for industry','It contains ~40% of India\'s coal reserves (Jharia coking coal) + uranium (Jaduguda) + iron ore + copper + mica','It is the largest state in India','It has the highest number of industrial cities'],
ans:1,
explain:'Jharkhand: Jharia coalfield = India\'s largest + highest quality coking coal. Jaduguda = India\'s only uranium mine (UCIL). Singhbhum = copper and iron ore. Koderma = world-class mica.',
wrongExplain:'Ruhr = Germany\'s industrial heartland with coal and steel. Jharkhand\'s mineral wealth makes it India\'s equivalent. But despite resources, Jharkhand has relatively low HDI — "resource curse" paradox.'},

{id:'q3_g_021',subject:'Geography',node:'g1',difficulty:'medium',year:2023,topic:'Jet Stream',
q:'The Western Jet Stream is significant for Indian weather because:',
opts:['It creates monsoon rainfall directly','Western Disturbances (winter rainfall in NW India for rabi crops) travel along the subtropical westerly jet stream from the Mediterranean','It is the primary driver of Bay of Bengal cyclones','It controls Himalayan glacier melting directly'],
ans:1,
explain:'Western Disturbances: Extra-tropical cyclones traveling along jet stream from Mediterranean/Atlantic. Bring snowfall to Himalayas + rainfall to Punjab, Haryana, UP, HP (Dec-March). Essential for rabi (wheat) crops.',
wrongExplain:'In summer, jet stream shifts north of Tibet — this allows Southwest Monsoon to advance northward over India. Jet stream controls both winter rainfall (Western Disturbances) and summer monsoon onset.'},

{id:'q3_g_022',subject:'Geography',node:'g2',difficulty:'hard',year:2020,topic:'EEZ',
q:'India\'s Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ) extends:',
opts:['12 nautical miles from baseline','200 nautical miles from baseline — covering 2.02 million sq km of marine resources','50 nautical miles','100 nautical miles + continental shelf'],
ans:1,
explain:'UNCLOS: EEZ = 200 nautical miles from baseline. India\'s EEZ = 2.02 million sq km (larger than India\'s land area). India\'s coastline = 7,516 km (including islands). Deep sea mining, fisheries, wind energy rights in EEZ.',
